'Sonogenetic' allows brain cells to be controlled by sound waves
The video shows how the threadworms change direction as soon as they are hit by sound vibrations.
Scientists have grown maggots with genetically modified nervous systems that can be controlled by sound wave bursts.
Tiny threadworms change direction as soon as they are hit by loud vibrations that humans can't hear.
The vibrations are activated by activating the genetically modified motor nerve cells to carry membrane channels that respond to trans-audio waves.
Related: Researchers read and write brain activity with light
Researchers said maggots have proven the power of a new procedure called Sonogenetics, so ultrasound can be used to activate a number of brain, heart and muscle cells from outside the body.
Sreekanth Chalasani, a researcher at the Salk Institute in La Jolla, California, told the Guardian that this procedure could one day replace deep-brain stimulation, an intrusive procedure that gives electrical vibrations into people’s brains to treat Parkinson’s disease symptoms.
Threadworms mostly do not react beyond sound, but Chalasani found that they reacted when they were surrounded by a liquid containing microscopic bubbles.
The bubbles he finds strengthen the ultrasound waves, allowing them to pass through the maggots.
The amplified sound waves affect structures in the membranes of some maggot cells called TRP-4 ion channels.
According to a report published in Nature Communications, sound waves allow these ion channels to open and activate the cells they are connected to.
In order to create threadworms controlled by ultrasound, Chalasani genetically modified the worms to allow some motor neurons to carry TRP-4 ion channels.
When he applied trans-audio to the altered creatures, the sound waves were amplified by microbubbles and transmitted into the maggots, where they also activated the altered motor neurons.
This procedure has similarities to optogenetics, a groundbreaking tool that allows scientists to activate and turn off neurons with light vibrations.
But Chalasani says sonogenetics may have some advantages over this technique.
Unlike light that needs to be sent across an optical fiber to the desired point in the brain, low-frequency ultrasound waves can pass through the tissue unimpeded and thus be sent through the skull into the brain.
“Using gene therapy and a therapeutic virus, we believe that targeted human neurons in the clinical setting for certain neurological treatments can be temporarily made sensitive to the trans-audio signal,” Chalasani said.
He added that other applications could focus on muscle cells and insulin-producing cells.
