How should the Semester Vacation be evaluated?
We asked Murat Ayd<0xC4><0xB1>n, an education expert-student coach, how should students evaluate their semester vacation.
Semester holidays should not be thought of as just rest, entertainment, spending time in front of television and computers.
Semester holidays are a very important opportunity to prepare for the new educational period and review the past.
The so-called leisure vacation is also an important opportunity for personal development, knowledge, skills and hobbies.
Make a semi-annual assessment list.
Write down everything you plan to do and try to implement it.
Make sure you enjoy it and you will have a very productive semester.
Now let’s talk about what a productive semester period should be for students who are preparing for YGS-LYS in the first place.
Because the questions that come to us most often from friends preparing for the YGS-LYS exams are: "How should we evaluate this period, should we solve a lot of questions, or should we solve the missing issues?"
In order to answer both these questions and to have a productive period, let us first begin with the advice of friends who prepare for the exam.
While the exam preparation process should be a process that normally starts from the 9th grade, we are trying to complete it more often in the last 1 year, which for us requires us to spend the last year more efficiently, efficiently, and using the time more accurately.
In addition to exam preparation, the senior student must also carry out the school’s written work together.
Although the graduate student who has completed the school has taken and experienced the exam (YGS-LYS) at least once, the year in which he will prepare for the exam as a graduate student is critical for him as well.
Because most graduate students and their parents see the "O" year as their last chance, which creates even greater stress.
Studying is the work that the student does not enjoy, only because he feels obligated, and therefore he usually leaves it at the end, but for the students who do it regularly, who make it a habit, it has become a task and what to do is always within a plan.
Now we have a semester break ahead of us, and we need to make the most of it.
We need to have a plan that will allow us to manage our time well.
Studying on a Semi-Year Vacation:
Everyone should have a plan that fits their situation first.
What was taken care of, what was lacking, should plan the day, the week, and the 15-day time.
During this period, there must be both repetitions of the subject and questions solutions.
At the same time, students who do not lack too much can solve an average of 1-2 trial exams.
Research shows that people forget 75 percent of what they learn in a week, 66 percent in a day, and 54 percent in an hour.
The best and most effective way to eliminate forgetting is to do it over and over again.
Students who make a lot of mistakes from past subjects in particular should focus on their general re-work.
Find out what you are missing and plan for the day, place the topics on each day, and make sure that they are addressed.
This planning will comfort you both academically and psychologically.
Make sure that when you put things in your plan, they are the ones you make the most mistakes.
Because you won’t have such a long vacation in the future.
Make Question Solutions:
It’s just as important to solve problems as to repeat them.
Because we can see how much we understand the work we do only through the feedback we receive through the question we solve.
Don’t forget to set a certain number of questions every day.
The number of questions you will solve may vary according to the work you will do on that day; you may not be able to solve a lot of questions in a day when you work on the subject, but we still need to do a certain amount of question solving in order to see how much we have learned about the topic that day.
Solve the Trial Exams:
Another study you will do on a half-year vacation should be to solve trial exams.
Although not all subjects are finished, you can at least make the lesson trial test solutions.
Let’s say that you have done a great deal of the Turkish lesson; you can solve 40 questions prepared Turkish lesson experiments.
And do it while you are doing it.
If you can solve 40 Turkish questions in 60 minutes at first, your next goal should be to solve them in a few minutes less if possible.
Vacation and Hobby Plan:
Of course, a vacation doesn’t just mean studying; you should also set aside a few days for your vacation, rest and hobbies.
A holiday period that will only be spent studying will prevent you from being discharged and resting.
Therefore, there should also be special times in your plans that you have to devote to yourself.
Reading books, watching TV, surfing the Internet can be part of your plans, and most importantly, how much time you will spend.
I have a little advice for those of you who haven’t had a good first year.
If my first semester didn’t go very well, I didn’t work hard and you say that I have a lot of shortcomings, this semester vacation is a great opportunity for you too.
But first you have to decide and believe it.
In the 2009–10 Turkish Super League, the most goals were scored between the 76th and 90th minutes.
Now answer the question you asked yourself, is the game over and you are going to the dressing room, or is the game still going on and there are so many minutes left to score?
I don't think anyone would want to say "we're going to look at the next game", which is a lost football team coach or a classic comment by his players.
All you have to do now is leave the past behind and look ahead, not walk, but run.
To summarize what we say:
1) Make a semester vacation plan in the first place,
2) Do it again by going over the things you know.
3) Resolve your missing issues.
4) Solve the issue by consolidating the issue,
5) Solve trial tests,
6) Read the book,
Set new goals for the new period.
Take time for yourself, your hobbies, and the things you enjoy.
9) Spend time with your family and friends,
10) Spend time on social and cultural activities (cinema, sports, theater, concerts, excursions, picnics, etc.)
